frameDefinitions: An Agent produces a Forgery, an entity that they intend to pass off as a particular (instance of)  a Standard.
An Entity is evaluated for whether or not it belongs to a particular Reference_category in a context where its category membership is doubtful.
An Agent performs an Action incorrectly.
An Agent acts in such a way as to give the incorrect impression to observers that a particular State_of_affairs holds.
A Figure is characterized as near the Ground, according to some contextually given scale.
frameExamples: So who was it that <t>faked</t> the photo 'showing' Jane Fonda and John Kerry with the Vietcong?

It can be hard to get your money back after discovering you've bought a <t>bogus</t>
autograph for hundreds or thousands of dollars!
Jordan <t>feigned</t> a love of jazz music to get her phone number .
She put her shoes <t>under</t> the table .
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person that creates a Forgery with the intent of passing it off as (an instance of) the <fen>Standard</fen>.
The <fen>Forgery</fen> is the product that the <fen>Agent</fen> creates with the intent of passing it off as (an instance of) the <fen>Standard</fen>.
The <fen>Standard</fen> is the actually existing or imagined (kind of) thing that the <fen>Agent</fen> wants to pass the <fen>Forgery</fen> off as.
The time at which the forgery takes place.
The location in which the <fen>Agent</fen> makes a <fen>Forgery</fen>.
The <fen>Entity</fen> that is being evaluated in terms of whether it is an instance of the <fen>Reference_category</fen>.
The type relative to which the <fen>Entity</fen> is evaluated.
The <fen>Agent</fen> performs an action incorrectly.
<fen>Patient</fen> is the entity affected by the <fen>Agent</fen>'s bungling of an <fen>Action</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Action</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> performs incorrectly.
The type of action that the <fen>Agent</fen> habitually bungles.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the bungling occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the bungling occurs.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person who acts in a misleading way to create the impression that a <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> holds.
This is the entity which is copied. With verbs it is frequently expressed as an NP Object: Pat <t>falsified</t> <fex name='Original'>the papers</fex>.
The Copy produced by the Creator most commonly occurs as the External Argument of a predicative use of an adjective or noun target: <fex name='Copy'>The painting</fex> is a <t>fake</t>.
The <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> is a an event, a state, or a property that the <fen>Agent</fen> wants others to believe have occurred or hold.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> feigns something.
The place in which the <fen>Agent</fen> feigns something.
The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location. The figure can be an entity or an event.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
listRoleExamples: <fex>The bomb found at the US Embassy in Berlin</fex> was fake.
The Austro-Hungarian Empire had a long history of <fex>military</fex> screw-ups.
A year after <fex>Audrey Seiler</fex> faked her own kidnapping while at college in Wisconsin, her lawyer says she's getting help and paying restitution.
A college student who staged <fex>her own disappearance</fex> last month will try to reach a plea agreement and avoid trial on charges she obstructed officers.
The cat is next to <fex>the mat</fex>.
<fex>The cat</fex> is next to the mat.
He was by the park <fex>on Friday</fex>.
